999.            221.118012      142.1     # extrapolation
#
# Results from the conversion into other commonly used units:
# In the wavelength range 300 to 650 nm we have:
#    2.60862e+12 photons / m^2 / s / sr
# In a pixel of diameter 4.100 cm at a mirror of 106.3 m^2 area and 15.00 m focal length we get:
#    1.79415e+09 photons per pixel / s (without any losses).
# In the V band we have a mean flux of 9.98773 microJansky/(arc sec)^2,
#    corresponding to magn. 21.40 / (arc sec)^2.
#
# For comparison, NSB measurements at the La Palma HEGRA/MAGIC site are:
#    Mirzoyan & Lorenz (1994): (1.75+-0.4) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr) in 300-600 nm range.
#    Preuss et al. (2002): (2.60+-0.35) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr) in 300-650 nm range
#      for Alt > 60 deg, |b| > 20 deg., no stars brighter than mag. 6.
# Scaling the Mirzoyan & Lorenz measurement to the 300-650 nm range of the Preuss et al.
# measurement, using the B&E spectral shape, would be (2.41+-0.55) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr)
# and the weighted average of the two would be (2.55+-0.30) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr),
# consistent with the spectrum as in this file.
#
# While the astro-ph/9909153 paper describes the spectrum just as "typical spectrum",
# the "Technical Note 115", apparently showing the same spectrum, describes it
# as taken in March 1991. That would be near solar maximum and the 1990-1992
# average V band sky brightness on La Palma in Table 1 of TN115 of magn. 21.5 / (arc sec)^2
# is consistent with the 21.40 derived above and with solar maximum expectations.
#
# Among the other non-SI units are those for the luminance, like the Lambert ("la"),
# or Stilb ("sb"), related to the SI unit for luminous intensity Candela ("cd"):
#  1 la = (1/pi) sb = (10^4/pi) cd/m^2.
# 1 Candela is the luminous intensity of a monochromatic light source of
# 540e12 Hertz frequency (i.e.555 nm) emitting a radiant intensity of 1/683 Watt / steradian.
# For other wavelengths the sensitivity curve of the human eye for bright light is applied.
# Thus better avoided and not really applicable for Cherenkov light background.
#
# A V band sky brightness of 22.0 mag within 1 (arc sec)^2,
# about the darkest sky ever observed in zenith for clear sky,
# corresponds to f_nu of 5.77 microJy/(arc sec)^2 near 550 nm or
# 8.10e9 photons/(nm s m^2 sr). According to darksky.org information sheet #99
# it corresponds to a luminance of 2e-4 cd/m^2 or 54 nanoLamberts
# (note: direct conversion at 550 nm - at the peak of the human eye efficacy -
# would result in about 84 nanoLamberts; the efficacy curve really matters).
# B&E TN115 quote a V band brightness of 21.9 mag for high elevation,
# high galactic latitude, high ecliptic latitude and near solar minimum,
# with typical increase of 0.4 mag at solar maximum, 0.4 mag at low ecliptic
# latitude, 0.25 mag at airmass 1.5 (zenith angle 48 deg.), and < 0.1 mag
# change during the night.
#
# For any conversion to astronomical magnitude units, keep in mind that
#    1 Jy = 10^-23 erg sec^-1 cm^-2 Hz^-1,
# resulting in the transformation
#    1 Jy = 1.51e7 photons sec^-1 m^-2 (dlambda/lambda)^-1
#
# The most physical magnitude system is the AB system, with
#    m(AB) = -2.5 log10(f_nu) - 48.60, with f_nu in erg/(s cm^2 Hz)
# or approximately
#    m(AB) = -2.5 log10(f_nu / 3610 Jy).
# The Johnson system has the following fluxes for magnitude zero:
# Filt. lambda  dlambda   mag 0
# name   [nm]   FWHM[nm]   [Jy]
# U 	 360	 150 	1810
# B 	 440	 220 	4260
# V 	 550 	 160	3640
# R 	 640	 230	3080
# I 	 790	 190	2550
#
# Transformations between AB and Johnson magnitudes:
#     B	=   B(AB) + 0.163
#     V	=   V(AB) + 0.044
#     R	=   R(AB) - 0.055
#     I	=   I(AB) - 0.309
#
# A conversion between V magnitudes per square arc seconds (ms2) and
# nanoLamberts (nL) is: nL = 34.08 exp(20.7233 - 0.92104 ms2)
# [Krisciunas and Schaefer, PASP 103 (1991), 1033.]
# The S10 unit (one mag 10 star per square degree) is 0.263 nL.
# Also from Krisciunas and Schaefer is the sky brightness b [nL] as a
# function of zenith angle:
#   b(z) = b(0) * 10^(-0.4*k*(X-1)) where X=(1-0.96*sin^2(z))^(-0.5)
# and k is the extinction coefficient in magnitudes per air mass X.
# They give the following set of equations for the sky brightness due
# to moon light at separations above 10 degrees:
#   I = 10^(-0.4*(3.84 + 0.026*abs(alpha) + 4e-9*alpha^4 - o))
#   f(rho) = 10^5.36 * (1.06+(cos(rho))^2) + 10^(6.15-rho/40)
#   X(z) = (1 - 0.96*(sin(z))^2)^(-0.5)
#   bm = f(rho) * I * 10^(-0.4*k*X(zm)) * (1-10^(-0.4*k*X(z)))
# with lunar phase angle: alpha [deg], moon/sky separation: rho, extinction
# coefficient: k, zenith angle of the moon: zm, zenith angle of the
# sky position: z. This is ignoring the "opposition effect" where the
# moon can be up to 35% brighter (for |alpha| < 7 deg), i.e. o=0.
# To include this effect use something like o(alpha)=0.32*exp(-0.5*(alpha/5 deg)^2).
# Resulting change in V-band sky brightness (no moon: b):
#   Delta V = -2.5*log10((bm + b(z))/b(z))
#
# The following are NSB brightess values for different moon phases
# (data from CTIO (A.R. Walker 1987), via wikipedia or from ESO):
#  Lunar Age 	U 	B 	V 	R 	I      z
# (days)
#        0     22.0    22.7    21.8    20.9    19.9    18.8
#        3     21.5    22.4    21.7    20.8    19.9    18.8
#        7     19.9    21.6    21.4    20.6    19.7    18.6
#       10     18.5    20.7    20.7    20.3    19.5    18.3
#       14     17.0    19.5    20.0    19.9    19.2    18.1
# with the values in the z filter band coming from
# http://www.eso.org/observing/etc/doc/helpfors.html#atmosphere .
# (Note that the spectrum of moon light is similar to the solar spectrum).
#
# A similar table for La Palma (http://www.tng.iac.es/info/la_palma_sky.html)
# Days from new moon
#              U       B       V       R       I       z Gunn
#        0     22.5    22.8    21.8    20.9    19.7    19.3
#        3     22.3    22.5    21.6    20.8    19.6    19.2
#        7     21.4    21.4    20.7    20.2    19.1    18.7
#       10     20.4    20.3    19.6    19.2    18.2    17.8
#       14     19.3    19.1    18.5    18.2    17.3    16.9
#
# Be aware that the two tables differ substantially in spectral behaviour
# (for CTIO differences in R and I are much smaller than at short
# wavelengths; for La Palma this is not the case).
#
# The Benn & Ellison spectral data should be valid far from the galactic plane,
# also from the ecliptic (little zodiacal light, which also has
# a different spectrum), apparently near solar maximum (not explicit
# in the paper but indicated in TN115), no moon, _between_ stars
# brighter than V=20 mag, corresponding (as reported by B&E TN 115 as 1990-1992 average)
# to values of B=22.5 mag/(arc sec)^2, V=21.5 mag/(arc sec)^2.
# Note that this is consistent with the value V=21.4 derived from the spectrum.
#
# Closer to the galactic plane, more and more star light gets included in
# the NSB seen by a Cherenkov telescope, with a mixture of stellar spectra.
#
# Zodiacal light as a function of ecliptic coordinates
# based on Leinert, in units of 10-8 W m^-2 sr^-1 micrometer^-1 m-^1 (????) at a wavelength of 500 nm
# "The scale factor to convert these units into photons cm^-2 s^-1 sr-^1 A^-1 is 252 at 5000 A; ie,
# the numbers in the table have to be multiplied by 252."
# (source: http://tauvex.iiap.res.in/tauwiki/index.php/Zodiacal_Light)
# For photons / (nm m^2 s sr) the conversion factor is then 2.52e7. Thus even at the poles
# of the ecliptic about a quarter of a V=22 mag/(arc sec)^2 sky is still zodiacal light.
#
# beta |   0       5       10      15      20      25      30      45      60      75      90 <- hel. long.
# ---- |   --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --
# 0    |                           3140    1610    985     640     275     150     100     77
# 5    |                           2940    1540    945     625     271     150     100     77
# 10   |                   4740    2470    1370    865     590     264     148     100     77
# 15   |   11500   6780    3440    1860    1110    755     525     251     146     100     77
# 20   |   6400    4480    2410    1410    910     635     454     237     141     99      77
# 25   |   3840    2830    1730    1100    749     545     410     223     136     97      77
# 30   |   2480    1870    1220    845     615     467     365     207     131     95      77
# 35   |   1650    1270    910     680     510     397     320     193     125     93      77
# 40   |   1180    940     700     530     416     338     282     179     120     92      77
# 45   |   910     730     555     442     356     292     250     166     116     90      77
# 60   |   505     442     352     292     243     209     183     134     104     86      77
# 75   |   338     317     269     227     196     172     151     116     93      82      77
# 90   |   259     251     225     193     166     147     132     104     86      79      77
# 105  |   212     210     197     170     150     133     119     96      82      77      77
# 120  |   188     186     177     154     138     125     113     90      77      74      77
# 135  |   179     178     166     147     134     122     110     90      77      73      77
# 150  |   179     178     165     148     137     127     116     96      79      72      77
# 165  |   196     192     179     165     151     141     131     104     82      72      77
# 180  |   230     212     195     178     163     148     134     105     83      72      77
# with a spectrum derived from the solar spectrum but - because of small scattering
# particles - expected to have somewhat higher relative intensity in the blue (?)
#
# And then there are all the stars brighter than V=20 in addition ...
